leicestershire's council leader byron rhodes says the funding system is "chaotic" and doesn't reflect real need. the county faces a £19m budget black hole due to government cuts. rhodes is working on a submission to restructure funding, seeking a fairer system with backing from local mps and councils.
pep guardiola says his first premier league season has been "not good enough". manchester city are fourth in the league, with the fa cup their only realistic chance of a trophy. guardiola promises to improve, saying "in the future i will be better - definitely".
welsh government minister alun davies withdrew plans for 10 marine conservation zones due to 7,000 strongly held responses. the marine conservation society called it an "embarrassing u-turn". davies will now assess existing 125 marine protected areas to identify gaps and potential improvements.
boris johnson, mayor of london, has backed the uk leaving the eu. he's a charismatic politician with a humorous persona and wide appeal. his decision may sway undecided voters and boost his standing among conservative grassroots, potentially positioning him for a future leadership role.
A lorry hit a broken-down bus on the A34 in Oxfordshire, injuring three people, one seriously. The bus, a rail replacement service, had 50 people on board when it was struck at 00:30 GMT. Passengers were taken to a police station or hospital for treatment.
Ricky Burns won the vacant WBA World Super-Lightweight title, becoming Scotland's first boxer to win world titles at three weights. He defeated Michele Di Rocco with a stoppage in the eighth round. Burns remains humble, crediting his team and seeking a big fight against top names like Adrien Broner.
adult social care firms struggle to hire and retain staff due to council budget cuts. councils in england face a £1.1bn shortfall, with £4.6bn cut from social care budgets since 2010. the sector warns of worsening care quality and urges government action to protect vulnerable services.
Lord Brian Rix, 92, a terminally ill actor and disability campaigner, has changed his stance on assisted dying, now supporting a law change. He finds his current state "unbearable" and wants to die peacefully. Rix urges the House of Lords to pass legislation allowing assisted dying.
Police in Northern Ireland discovered a "terrorist hide" in Capanagh Forest, uncovering arms including an armour-piercing rocket and anti-personnel mines. The find is believed to be linked to dissident republicans, with police saying an attack is "highly likely". The seizure is considered significant, with many devices ready to deploy.
kenyan election results are delayed due to electronic system issues. returning officers are delivering paper copies of results to the counting centre. uhuru kenyatta leads with 53% of votes, but raila odinga's allies are confident he will gain ground as more results are declared.
maria de villota, a formula 1 driver, lost her right eye in a test track crash at duxford airfield. she was driving the mr-01 car for the marussia team when it hit a support truck. de villota remains in a critical but stable condition after a lengthy operation.
the us supreme court upheld a key part of obama's healthcare law, preserving insurance for millions. the 6-3 decision allows tax subsidies for low-income individuals to continue. the ruling is a major victory for president obama, but republicans vowed to continue fighting the law.
russia's new law restricts social media users, requiring bloggers with 3,000+ daily readers to register. internet companies must allow authorities access to user data stored on russian servers. critics call the move "draconian" and a crackdown on free expression, amid concerns over government control.
western sahara welcomes morocco's return to the african union after 32 years. morocco controls two-thirds of western sahara, which some see as africa's last colony. the au's readmission of morocco may help resolve the territory's status, with western sahara hoping for a referendum.
arcade fire revived glastonbury's spirits with a party atmosphere after an electric storm stopped the festival. the canadian band's anthems and dancers lifted the crowd. frontman win butler called it a "highlight" in the band's history, ending with a mass singalong to their signature song, wake up.
mead, an ancient drink, is making a comeback in the us. commercial meaderies have grown from 30 to 250 in the last decade. industry leaders aim to raise awareness and improve the drink's image, shedding its sweet and medieval reputation to appeal to modern drinkers.
lady gaga will perform at the super bowl half-time show, following in the footsteps of iconic performers like michael jackson and prince. past shows have featured memorable moments, including mishaps and powerful performances. gaga must deliver within a 12-minute time limit, a challenging task for any artist.
us president barack obama said david cameron became "distracted" after the 2011 libya intervention. obama said the operation was a success, but libya is now "a mess". the uk and us have responded, with downing street saying they "deeply value" their partnership on national security and foreign policy objectives.
Dawn Purvis is stepping down as director of Northern Ireland's Marie Stopes clinic on April 24. She led the clinic since its launch in 2012, providing early medical abortions under strict legal controls. Purvis will take on a new role on the clinic's advisory board.
inverness caledonian thistle lost 3-0 to st johnstone, falling four points adrift at the foot of the scottish premiership. larnell cole's red card sealed the contest, and liam craig's penalty and graham cummins' goals secured the win. inverness' relegation woes worsened with the loss.
scottish deputy first minister john swinney will make a statement on the named person scheme. the scheme aims to appoint a named person to ensure every child's wellbeing. the supreme court previously ruled against information sharing proposals, citing concerns over privacy and family life under the european convention on human rights.
neil lennon has joined hibernian as manager, bringing experience and profile to the championship club. he has a proven track record of building and motivating teams, and will aim to deliver promotion. lennon's appointment is mutually beneficial, offering him a chance to rejuvenate his career and achieve success.
uk manufacturing activity contracted in april, with the markit/cips index falling to 49.2. the decline was attributed to soft domestic demand, falling new orders, and eu referendum uncertainty. the sector's contraction may drag on the economy, with predicted job losses and a slowdown in production.
prison officer adrian ismay, 52, died 11 days after a dissident republican bomb attack in belfast. a post-mortem examination confirmed he died from his injuries. a man has been charged with attempted murder and an inquiry is ongoing, with police appealing for information on two cars used by the bombers.
uk prime minister david cameron will host an anti-corruption summit in london, aiming to expose and punish global corruption. world leaders, businesses, and charities will attend to discuss reforms. the summit seeks to put corruption at the "top of the international agenda" to drive out exploitation and promote economic growth.
english doctors are being paid to limit patient referrals to hospitals. at least nine clinical commissioning groups offer payments for hitting targets, sparking concerns that patients may miss vital care. the british medical association says such incentives are "misguided" and erode patient-doctor trust.
a chinese woman claimed her husband divorced her due to her "fat face". she underwent three facial surgeries, but was left with soreness and sued the hospital. the story sparked outrage online, with many questioning the woman's motives and the validity of her claims.
welwyn garden city's coronation fountain was turned off due to the hosepipe ban. the council is buying water from a landscaping company to fill it for jubilee celebrations. the water is from a natural lake source and is considered surplus, making it a sustainable solution.
harper lee's to kill a mockingbird, published 50 years ago, remains her only novel. lee's friend, thomas lane butts, reveals she stopped writing due to the deprivation of privacy she experienced. the book, inspired by her hometown, addressed racism and justice, bringing civic pride to monroeville, alabama.
adam peaty defended his 50m breaststroke title, finishing in 25.99 seconds. he completed a double-double at the world aquatics championships, having also won the 100m title. peaty's impressive display earned praise from fellow swimmers, with some hailing him as a phenomenal athlete.
The parents of a motorbike rider killed by a drunk driver in 2010 have spoken out against proposed reforms, saying life sentences do not go far enough. Chris and Sue Moores want increased sentences backed by manslaughter charges. They believe drink driving and killing someone should be considered manslaughter.
nine british nationals, including four children, were detained in turkey for allegedly trying to enter syria illegally. the group is being held at a police station awaiting deportation to the uk. this incident follows several recent cases of british individuals being stopped from traveling to syria.
A church in North Yorkshire has spent £10,000 building bat lofts to encourage a colony to leave, but they remain, soiling the interior. The bats are protected by law, making removal difficult. The church struggles to maintain the 11th-century building due to the "appalling smell" and damage.
Baltimore's mayor, Stephanie Rawlings-Blake, fired Police Commissioner Anthony Batts, citing his leadership as a distraction from addressing the city's crime surge. Batts will be replaced by Deputy Kevin Davis as interim police chief. The city has seen a 48% increase in homicides this year.
Asghar Buksh, 55, admitted killing his wife Nasreen, 43, with a blunt object while she slept. He claimed to have no memory of the incident, citing an acute stress disorder. Buksh will be sentenced on June 27, with the court to consider background reports.
ukip's ruling body rejected a call to deselect michelle brown, a welsh assembly member, despite complaints she was "abrasive and discourteous". the letter did not follow proper process, the party chairman said. ukip also allowed 11 candidates, including anti-islam campaigner anne marie waters, to run for the party leadership.
a chinese cult member trial began in yantai, shandong province. the cult, church of the almighty god, killed 37-year-old wu shuoyan at a mcdonald's for refusing to give her phone number. hundreds of cult members were detained after the brutal killing sparked public outrage.
england drew the first test against pakistan, finishing 25 runs short of a victory target. adil rashid took five wickets, turning the match in england's favor. england's performance was impressive, filling them with confidence ahead of the second test in dubai, despite a frustrating finish.
A 6,000-year-old "eco-home" was discovered near Stonehenge, featuring a tree stump wall and stone-lined pit. Archaeologists are concerned a planned tunnel could damage the site. They are urging the route to be moved to preserve the ancient landscape and its crucial organic remains.
egyptian internet activists played a key role in pro-democracy protests. they used social media to organize and mobilize, but emphasize that the movement is about people, not just online tools. the internet helped build momentum, but it was police violence that brought people together.
Edinburgh's winter festivals generated £241m for the city. Almost 1 million people visited during the six-week period, with 890,000 attending Christmas events and 150,000 attending Hogmanay celebrations. The revenue benefits local businesses, including retail, food, and accommodation, not the event organisers or city council.
bhs' fate will be decided on thursday. retailer greg tufnell's bid, backed by portuguese money, is the front-runner. if a deal isn't struck, bhs may be liquidated, with administrators lining up firms to break up the business and sell it off piecemeal, potentially cherry-picking profitable stores.
A UK firm plans to introduce PooPrints, a US service using DNA to identify dog owners who don't clean up after their pets. Councils may require owners to register their dogs' DNA via a mouth swab. This aims to create cleaner, safer public spaces, with 15 councils showing interest.
scotland's sport funding faces a 20% cut over three years. the reduction, blamed on decreased government spending and lottery sales, may impact elite athletes and lead to job losses. the scottish government claims it will continue to invest in sport and physical activity to promote a healthy scotland.
welsh parties prepare for the next election. the conservatives are boosted after recent gains, while labour faces challenges, including dissatisfaction with the nhs and council reorganization. other parties, including plaid cymru and the liberal democrats, also regroup and plan for the next election.
almost half of scotland's fostered teenagers have lived with three or more families. the fostering network warns that 750 more foster carers are urgently needed to provide stability. the group urges people to open their hearts and homes to vulnerable youngsters to improve their education and wellbeing.
historical chinese documents reveal hainan gibbons were once widespread across half of china. the apes began to disappear 150 years ago, corresponding with population growth and deforestation. today, only 26-28 hainan gibbons remain, living in isolated forest patches in southwest china, sparking hopes for conservation efforts.
four telford academies were put in special measures within a week. inspectors criticized teaching, leadership, and a "culture of low expectations" at phoenix academy and lakeside academy. ofsted also faulted the trust's support and said each school is considering an alternative sponsor.
over 1 million eu citizens petitioned against ttip trade talks with the us. they fear the deal threatens democracy, the nhs, and environmental standards. the petition may lead to a public hearing in the european parliament, but the commission says it doesn't qualify as a formal european citizens' initiative.
Diageo's Distill Ventures invests in Melbourne's Starward Whisky to expand into new export markets. The investment will increase production of Starward's single malts and develop new innovations. This marks Distill's second whisky investment, following Denmark's Stauning Whisky, as Diageo taps into growing global recognition of Australian whisky.
Ruskin College is cutting three courses, moving away from its founding principles of serving working-class adults and mature students. The college's governing body cited low student numbers for the decision. Students and alumni are campaigning to save the affected courses, citing the college's unique focus on accessible education.
The inquest into the 1976 IRA massacre of 10 Protestant workers at Kingsmill has been delayed due to a lack of coroners. Senior Coroner John Leckey's retirement will leave only one coroner in Northern Ireland. Families of victims are demanding more resources to allow the inquest to proceed.
Rare Leonardo da Vinci drawings from the Queen's collection are on display at Nottingham Castle. The exhibit features a portrait of St Anne, sketches, and technical drawings, showcasing da Vinci's skill. Almost 600 of his drawings are in the Royal Collection, considered the richest and most technically brilliant.
